He had before said, (vs. 3.) aeta haee res est.- perii! being in fear for himself, and the project he had concerted. Now, quid istic nar-rat? whic . must be taken as if Syrus approved of what the old man had said, joined in the reproof. “What can Clitipho say for himself now? what has he to answer ? ’¹ Whenoe Clitipho, perii! ⁴⁴ I am undone1’' What, is he my enemy too? does he help to spirit up my father against me? 39. Fuit quaedam anus. Syrus pretends that he had concerted this against Menedemus, to obtain some money of him for this courtezan. This was specious enough, yet Chremes is dissatisfied with it. However, it is of service in the end; for when Antiphila was dis- covered to be Chremes' daughter, he could not avoid paying the price of her ransom, and thus out of his own pocket furnish the money wanting for Bacchis—40.
